{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512207"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:51:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:51:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11859"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11859"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.58,0.14,0.15,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4459"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101528"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4459"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11859"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83967"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1675"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"10962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6440"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16682"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34793"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42674"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44646"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101528"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man is being reviewed by his general practitioner for his annual medical review.  The patient states that he feels well, except for episodes of dizziness if he stands up suddenly after being seated for a while. He has a medical history of type 2 diabetes, coronary artery disease, ischaemic cardiomyopathy and benign prostatic hyperplasia. His current medications are tamsulosin, prazosin, aspirin, metoprolol, atorvastatin and metformin. He exercises daily and eats a well-balanced diet.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his resting blood pressure is 130/84 mmHg and pulse 70/min. He is asked to stand for one minute and his blood pressure on standing measures 105/60 mmHg and pulse 78/min. The rest of the examination is normal, as is an ECG.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No change in current medication regimen","Cease the prazosin","Cease the tamsulosin","Cease the metoprolol","Start fludrocortisone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is shown to have orthostatic hypotension. Defined as a drop of 20 mmHg systolic or 10 mmHg diastolic within three minutes of standing, orthostatic hypotension occurs when the compensatory mechanism of sympathetic flow fails to compensate for the pooling of 500ml-1L of blood in the legs. This is more common in older individuals due to the weak baroreceptors, but can also have iatrogenic causes. This patient has symptomatic orthostatic hypotension and will need some revision of his medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrazosin\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0is a alpha-1 adrenergic receptor antagonist. Prazosin use can be associated with significant first dose hypotension, orthostatic hypotension and syncope. If needed in the elderly population, prazosin should be initiated at the lower end of the dosing range.\u00a0Of all the medications that this patient is taking, ceasing the prazosin is most likely to improve his symptomatic orthostatic hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETamsulosin\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0is a longer acting uroselective alpha 1 blocker targeting the predominant receptor prostate and bladder smooth muscle. Tamsulosin can cause orthostatic hypotension, but at lower rates compared to agents such as prazosin. If the patient continued to experience postural hypotension after prazosin cessation, consideration could be given to changing tamsulosin to dutasteride and/or reducing the dose of metoprolol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetoprolol\u00a0\u003C/strong\u003Eis a cardioselective beta 1 adrenergic blocker affecting heart rate and myocardial contractility.\u00a0Patients taking metoprolol can experience hypotension, especially when it used with other antihypertensive drugs, although it has a lesser pronounced blood-pressure lowering effect compared to other medications. Continuing the beta blocker would be in the patient\u0027s best interest from a cardiovascular perspective given the patient\u0027s diagnosis of ischaemic cardiomyopathy. If the patient continued to experience postural hypotension after prazosin cessation, consideration could be given to reducing the dose of metoprolol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFludrocortisone\u00a0\u003C/strong\u003Eis a synthetic mineralocorticoid which can be used in the management of refractory postural hypotension. It promotes renal reabsorption of sodium and excretion of potassium. The resultant sodium retention increases blood volume, thus leading to higher blood pressure. Prior to initiating such medications, it is important to try conservative measures and remove iatrogenic culprits i.e. prazosin in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Polypharmacy and adverse drug reactions are a common problem in the elderly population","Orthostatic hypotension can be associated with prazosin"],"references":["Bird ST, Delaney JA, Brophy JM, Etminan M, Skeldon SC, Hartzema AG. Tamsulosin treatment for benign prostatic hyperplasia and risk of severe hypotension in men aged 40-85 years in the United States: Risk window analyses using between and within patient methodology. BMJ. 2013;347(nov05 3). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24192967/","Palma J-A, Kaufman H. Mechanisms, causes, and evaluation of orthostatic hypotension. In: UpToDate [online]. 2022 [cited 2022Sep5]. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/mechanisms-causes-and-evaluation-of-orthostatic-hypotension#H11","Boudonas GE. \u03b2-Blockers in coronary artery disease management. Hippokratia. 2010 Oct;14(4):231-5. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3031314/","Lee PH, Park G-M, Han S, Kim Y-G, Lee J-Y, Roh J-H, et al. Beta-blockers provide a differential survival benefit in patients with coronary artery disease undergoing contemporary post-percutaneous coronary intervention management. Scientific Reports. 2020;10(1). Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33335231/","Joseph P, Swedberg K, Leong DP, Yusuf S. The evolution of \u03b2-blockers in coronary artery disease and heart failure (part 1/5). Journal of the American College of Cardiology. 2019;74(5):672\u201382. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31370960/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83967"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11859"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83967"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-02T13:54:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T13:56:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4459"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101528"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type